Abstract:

    First the topic (comprehension). Then a fuller description of the topic (models of narrative comprehension and their deficiencies). Then the approach (review, compare, evaluate). Then the findings (the models are deficient, but can be improved in THESE ways). Then the conclusion (the models are deficient, but can be improved in THESE ways, and this is important because it will help us understand how people comprehend narratives).

    I'm interpreting paper components as functions passed as arguments into a class instance that encodes information based on the function's content. The docstring for my abstract would roughly be "conveys a overview of the paper". It's a good overview if it's accurate and conveys enough information that a reader knows what it's about and what to expect. A test of the implementation of this specification would depend on both its content and the content of the overall paper.

    - Maybe needs one more wrap-up sentence after list of priorities I'll emphasize
    - Abstract focuses on models, but I might have to mention "approaches" or otherwise provide a broad definition of model. 
    What is a model anyway? How do I distinguish it from "formal account"?  And it's possible that even the discourse analyses supported by story grammar theory don't amount to models either depending on the standards of the reader. I'm not all that interested in being snobbish about the distinction, but may need to address it.

    - Abstract names fostering deeper inateraction with other areas of memory research, but I don't really address that much in my paper. 
    